| Trivia                  = * Filming began on April 27, 2015 - the same day as the Marvel Studios film ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]''. This was announced through a video showing Kodi Smit McPhee teleport as Nightcrawler.
* Similar to ''[[X-Men: Days of Future Past (film)|X-Men: Days of Future Past]]'', an episode of the original ''{{WP|Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek}}'' series that features a slightly similar plot element is playing in the background of one of the scenes. In this film, it's the episode "{{WP|Who Mourns for Adonais?}}", which features a powerful man claiming to be a god.
* "{{WP|Kill 'Em All#Track listing|The Four Horsemen}}" is the name of the song playing in the background of the scene where Apocalypse recruits Angel. It was released on the {{WP|Metallica}} album {{WP|Kill 'Em All}} in 1983, which is the year the film takes place in.
* The song playing in the background during the Quicksilver speed sequence is "{{WP|Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)}}" by {{WP|Eurythmics}}. The single was also released in 1983.
* After watching ''{{WP|Return of the Jedi}}'' in theaters, Jubilee argues that ''{{WP|The Empire Strikes Back}}'' is still the best among the three ''Star Wars'' films while Scott argues that {{WP|Star Wars (film)|the first one}} is still the best. Jean then says at least they can all agree that the third film in a series is always the worst. This is an allusion to the fact that ''[[X-Men: The Last Stand]]'', the third film in the first ''X-Men'' trilogy, was poorly received by audiences. It's also ironic given that ''Apocalypse'' is the third film in this second ''X-Men'' trilogy.{{cite|ref=true|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Why-X-Men-Apocalypse-Made-An-X-Men-Last-Stand-Joke-133567.html|title=Why X-Men: Apocalypse Made An X-Men: The Last Stand Joke|work=Cinemablend|first=Adam|last=Holmes|date=27 May 2016|accessdate=27 May 2016}}
* Logan's Weapon X look in the film is strikingly similar to his [[Marvel Comics Presents Vol 1 79|Weapon X look in the comics]].
* Professor X's line, "I feel a great swell of pity for the poor soul who comes to that school looking for trouble," is lifted directly from ''[[X-Men (film)|X-Men]]''. The line is also said to Magneto.
* The movie's ending was originally meant to double as tease of a Gambit film that was in development at the time. The movie's final scene involves [[Essex Corporation (Earth-10005 Revised)|Essex Corporation]], and [[Nathaniel Essex (Earth-10005 Revised)|Mister Sinister]] was going to be appear in the Gambit movie.{{cite|ref=true|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/x-men-mister-sinister-gambit-movie-villain-channing-tatum-fox|title=X-Men: Mister Sinister Was Supposed to Debut in Channing Tatum's Gambit Movie|work=IGN|first=Jesse|last=Scheden|date=27 May 2020|accessdate=27 May 2020}}

